    Introduction

    In this lab you will install and configure IIS to serve dynamic content. IIS is a web server and you will configure it to serve content that has been generated by a Python script, this is a similar idea to running dynamic content via php.

    Connect to Azure Lab Services
  1. If you do not have a copy of Python on your server install it now. This will need Internet access.

    2. [help]
    The easiest way to do this if you don't already have Internet access is to add a network card in VMwarwe. Make sure this is a NAT card. Go to http://www.google.com/chrome and download and install the 64 bit version for Windows. This will generate security warnings. You can safely ignore them.
    In order to get the download to work you will need to turn on the download support. This can be done in the Internet Setting - top right of the browser window.
  2. Run a command prompt then type pip install flask. This will need Internet access.

    3. [help]
    The easiest way to do this if you don't already have Internet access is to add a network card in VMwarwe. Make sure this is a NAT card.
  3. If the server manager isn't running start it.

    4.  
  4. Click on "Add roles and features"

    5.  
  5. Click through the installation process until you reach Server Roles.

    6.  
  6. Click through the installation process until you get to Web Server Role (IIS) -> Role Services. Select ASP.NET 4.7 and finish the installation.

    7.  
  7. Download HTTP Platform from https://www.iis.net/downloads/microsoft/httpplatformhandler and install it.

    8.  
  8. Go back to the Server Manager and start the the Internet Information Services (IIS) Manager.

    9.  
  9. Select "Default Web Site" then double click on Handler Mappings.

    10.  
  10. Click on add Module Mapping.

    11.  
  11. Add a module mapping as shown below.

    12.  
  12. Add a module mapping as shown below.

    13.  
  13. Edit and save c:\inetpub\wwwroot\web.config so that it looks as follow.

    14.  
  14. Create a c:\webapp folder

    15.  
  15. Open notepad and enter the following program, then save it as c:\webapp\app.py

    16.  
  16. Start a web browser(You may want to download and install chrome rather than use IE.) on your Windows server and set the address to http://localhost/. You should see a Hello World message. Change the URL to http://localhost/?name=Fred and the message should change to Hello Fred.

    17. [help]
    The easiest way to do this if you don't already have Internet access is to add a network card in VMwarwe. Make sure this is a NAT card. Go to http://www.google.com/chrome and download and install the 64 bit version for Windows. This will generate security warnings. You can safely ignore them.
    In order to get the download to work you will need to turn on the download support. This can be done in the Internet Setting - top right of the browser window.
  17. Change app.py so that it displays a form where you can enter your name. When you press submit it should say hello to you by name, for example for me I'd enter Martin and it would say Hello Martin.

    18.  
  18. Combine this script with the Active Directory scripts you were given to create a simple phonebook application. The user should be able to enter a name in a web page and the script looks up information about people matching that name in Active Directory. The script should return names, email address and a telephone number.

    19. [help]
    The easiest way to do this if you don't already have Internet access is to add a network card in VMwarwe. Make sure this is a NAT card.
